00:04:18.079 --> 00:04:21.930
And it really has, in many
ways, a folkloric story.

00:04:21.930 --> 00:04:23.520
When Peter came to
me and said--

00:04:23.520 --> 00:04:24.800
I'm like, oh, I've
heard that story.

00:04:24.800 --> 00:04:27.550
So I think we'd really to hear
from the horse's mouth.

00:04:27.550 --> 00:04:30.910
So can you tell us a little bit
about how Udacity came to

00:04:30.910 --> 00:04:33.410
be and what it really is?

00:04:33.410 --> 00:04:35.480
SEBASTIAN THRUN: I give
you the Cliff Notes.

00:04:35.480 --> 00:04:38.790
About two years ago, Peter
Norvig-- who's a director here

00:04:38.790 --> 00:04:41.510
at Google-- and I tend to teach
this class, Artificial

00:04:41.510 --> 00:04:42.570
Intelligence, at Stanford.

00:04:42.570 --> 00:04:45.810
And we listened to Sal Khan
talk about how his Khan

00:04:45.810 --> 00:04:48.130
Academy reached tens of
millions of kids.

00:04:48.130 --> 00:04:49.930
And honestly, we got jealous
and inspired.

00:04:49.930 --> 00:04:51.580
So we took our class online.

00:04:51.580 --> 00:04:53.020
We sent out one email.

00:04:53.020 --> 00:04:54.950
And we got 160,000 students.

00:04:54.950 --> 00:04:56.350
And we were blown away.

00:04:56.350 --> 00:04:58.590
But more so we were blown away
by the type of students.

00:04:58.590 --> 00:05:00.700
These are people from
all trades of life.

00:05:00.700 --> 00:05:02.560
Kids as young as 11 years old.

00:05:02.560 --> 00:05:03.710
People really old.

00:05:03.710 --> 00:05:05.240
Soldiers in Afghanistan.

00:05:05.240 --> 00:05:06.980
Mothers raising kids alone.

00:05:06.980 --> 00:05:09.660
So we felt we could reach
a huge number of people.

00:05:09.660 --> 00:05:12.520
And we've taken this to a great
new level at Udacity.

00:05:12.520 --> 00:05:14.500
We've been working with a number
of companies, Google

00:05:14.500 --> 00:05:17.210
being one of them, to really
bring to people the type of

00:05:17.210 --> 00:05:19.540
skills that they need in the
work force to really get ready

00:05:19.540 --> 00:05:21.240
for jobs in this space.

00:05:21.240 --> 00:05:23.750
If you look at HTML5, it's
singly the most exciting thing

00:05:23.750 --> 00:05:25.310
happening in computer
science today.

00:05:25.310 --> 00:05:26.700
And no college teaches it.

00:05:26.700 --> 00:05:28.990
So you can't get that skill
in a university.

00:05:28.990 --> 00:05:29.735
And why don't colleges
teach it?

00:05:29.735 --> 00:05:32.840
Well, it's so new that Google
cares about it.

00:05:32.840 --> 00:05:34.260
And many other companies do.

00:05:34.260 --> 00:05:35.880
But college professors haven't
quite caught up.

00:05:35.880 --> 00:05:37.420
So we try to fill that gap.

00:05:37.420 --> 00:05:39.490
KATHERINE MILLER: That's
really incredible.

00:05:39.490 --> 00:05:41.690
And as I was chatting with
Peter yesterday, he said

00:05:41.690 --> 00:05:46.440
there's actually a technology
tie in to how Udacity was

00:05:46.440 --> 00:05:48.420
built, a connection
with Google.

00:05:48.420 --> 00:05:52.240
So with our audience where we're
trying to inspire them

00:05:52.240 --> 00:05:54.580
to be using Google technology,
we'd love to hear a little bit

00:05:54.580 --> 00:05:57.557
about the underbelly
of Udacity if

00:05:57.557 --> 00:05:57.830
you'd like to share.

00:05:57.830 --> 00:06:00.010
SEBASTIAN THRUN: We would not be
alive without Google's App

00:06:00.010 --> 00:06:02.270
Engine, without Google's
amazing expertise.

00:06:02.270 --> 00:06:03.220
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:03.220 --> 00:06:05.160
SEBASTIAN THRUN: Starting a
company that basically spans

00:06:05.160 --> 00:06:08.450
all the way from instructional
design videos, quizzing, to

00:06:08.450 --> 00:06:10.810
learning management, which is
the kind of [? source ?] that

00:06:10.810 --> 00:06:12.370
keeps track of your progress.

