To teach our portals and
[INAUDIBLE] teach us to

00:06:14.230 --> 00:06:15.560
understand what's going on.

00:06:15.560 --> 00:06:16.880
All within a year?

00:06:16.880 --> 00:06:18.560
It would have been completely
impossible.

00:06:18.560 --> 00:06:21.080
So now it's possible because
Google is just such an amazing

00:06:21.080 --> 00:06:23.300
company with so many
amazing services.

00:06:23.300 --> 00:06:27.010
But specifically excited that
we're also working with Google

00:06:27.010 --> 00:06:29.550
in my home country on educating
the world and

00:06:29.550 --> 00:06:30.855
bringing that content.

00:06:30.855 --> 00:06:33.070
KATHERINE MILLER:
That's amazing.

00:06:33.070 --> 00:06:35.970
And Peter, now, the other
side of that.

00:06:35.970 --> 00:06:39.230
You had this amazing idea for
a course and needed to bring

00:06:39.230 --> 00:06:40.436
that to life.

00:06:40.436 --> 00:06:40.960
PETER LUBBERS: Yeah.

00:06:40.960 --> 00:06:42.960
When I joined Google,
I'd come from a

00:06:42.960 --> 00:06:44.840
background of HTML5 training.

00:06:44.840 --> 00:06:49.820
But this was instructor-led,
fly to some other country,

00:06:49.820 --> 00:06:51.860
teach 10 people for two days.

00:06:51.860 --> 00:06:55.590
And when I joined Google, one
of, of course, the main things

00:06:55.590 --> 00:06:58.260
is we do things at
a large scale.

00:06:58.260 --> 00:07:00.327
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:00.327 --> 00:07:04.150
PETER LUBBERS: So it was like,
how do you scale that up to--

00:07:04.150 --> 00:07:05.240
SEBASTIAN THRUN: 40 people.

00:07:05.240 --> 00:07:05.810
PETER LUBBERS: Yeah.

00:07:05.810 --> 00:07:06.150
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:06.150 --> 00:07:07.060
PETER LUBBERS: How do
you double that?

00:07:07.060 --> 00:07:09.650
And so the other thing at
Google, we're very interested

00:07:09.650 --> 00:07:11.490
always in metrics.

00:07:11.490 --> 00:07:15.150
And so one of the things about
a lot of the typical classic

00:07:15.150 --> 00:07:18.610
online learning is you don't--

00:07:18.610 --> 00:07:20.250
people go to a page.

00:07:20.250 --> 00:07:22.090
They maybe look at a tutorial.

00:07:22.090 --> 00:07:24.830
But we can't really tell whether
they've tried it.

00:07:24.830 --> 00:07:28.050
A page view, ultimately,
is a vanity metric.

00:07:28.050 --> 00:07:29.930
You can have 100,000
page views.

00:07:29.930 --> 00:07:31.200
And nobody's learned anything.

00:07:31.200 --> 00:07:37.170
So really it was kind of great
luck to kind of run into each

00:07:37.170 --> 00:07:37.920
other in that space.

00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:40.830
But we were really looking
at, how can we scale?

00:07:40.830 --> 00:07:43.300
And how can we get
deeper metrics?

00:07:43.300 --> 00:07:46.590
And now we can see who's
done a certain video.

00:07:46.590 --> 00:07:48.660
But right after the videos--
and we'll talk a little bit

00:07:48.660 --> 00:07:49.620
more about it later--

00:07:49.620 --> 00:07:50.920
you get a challenge.

00:07:50.920 --> 00:07:52.710
And you actually have
to do some coding.

00:07:52.710 --> 00:07:56.250
And so with that in mind,
you really have--

00:07:56.250 --> 00:08:00.180
we can see, hey, everyone was
able to pass this challenge.

00:08:00.180 --> 00:08:01.210
But this one is really bad.

00:08:01.210 --> 00:08:03.464
Probably reflects bad
on us as teachers.

00:08:03.464 --> 00:08:04.268
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:04.268 --> 00:08:08.523
PETER LUBBERS: But the deeper
metrics, the scale, it's a

00:08:08.523 --> 00:08:09.910
match made in heaven.

00:08:09.910 --> 00:08:10.440
KATHERINE MILLER: Mmhmm.

00:08:10.440 --> 00:08:11.730
That's really incredible.

00:08:11.730 --> 00:08:15.990
