They worked overtime on
being translators.

00:22:49.245 --> 00:22:50.940
KATHERINE MILLER: Excellent.

00:22:50.940 --> 00:22:53.120
One thing that I think is really
interesting from what

00:22:53.120 --> 00:22:54.290
you've said, though--
especially the

00:22:54.290 --> 00:22:56.430
interactivity piece--

00:22:56.430 --> 00:22:59.220
I actually have a background
in higher education.

00:22:59.220 --> 00:23:03.370
And when this massively open
online coursework started

00:23:03.370 --> 00:23:09.690
coming out, my first reaction
was, how does that work with

00:23:09.690 --> 00:23:12.250
some of the benefits or
potential perceived strengths

00:23:12.250 --> 00:23:13.510
of a more traditional
environment?

00:23:13.510 --> 00:23:17.190
Kind of the infrastructure of
the student body and academic

00:23:17.190 --> 00:23:20.470
affairs and all of those things
that can, hopefully,

00:23:20.470 --> 00:23:22.230
drive people to success.

00:23:22.230 --> 00:23:24.150
But it sounds like,
in many ways--

00:23:24.150 --> 00:23:27.050
I think the word somebody had
mentioned was self-governing.

00:23:27.050 --> 00:23:30.480
It seems like these people
have actually created

00:23:30.480 --> 00:23:34.480
communities that are keeping
them enrolled in the courses

00:23:34.480 --> 00:23:36.115
and moving forward.

00:23:36.115 --> 00:23:38.180
SEBASTIAN THRUN: We live
in the 21st century.

00:23:38.180 --> 00:23:40.520
And it's time for us to go
to the 21st century now.

00:23:40.520 --> 00:23:41.830
KATHERINE MILLER: I know.

00:23:41.830 --> 00:23:43.960
When I was studying, it was
right on the border of that

00:23:43.960 --> 00:23:44.820
21st century.

00:23:44.820 --> 00:23:47.935
So we hadn't quite tipped the
balance in my classes yet.

00:23:47.935 --> 00:23:49.560
SEBASTIAN THRUN: I had this
painful experience.

00:23:49.560 --> 00:23:52.220
I'm trying to partially cover
curriculum with the way it's

00:23:52.220 --> 00:23:52.640
being taught.

00:23:52.640 --> 00:23:55.205
And do some crazy great
things like just go to

00:23:55.205 --> 00:23:57.050
HTML5 and just do it.

00:23:57.050 --> 00:23:59.170
And in the class curriculum,
there's something called

00:23:59.170 --> 00:24:00.710
factoring polynomials.

00:24:00.710 --> 00:24:02.860
It's like you take a long
polynomial and you have to

00:24:02.860 --> 00:24:04.020
break it into pieces.

00:24:04.020 --> 00:24:05.440
And I'm a Stanford professor.

00:24:05.440 --> 00:24:06.960
I've done math all my life.

00:24:06.960 --> 00:24:09.550
And I've never ever factored a
polynomial in my entire life.

00:24:09.550 --> 00:24:11.930
And I know nobody in the planet
who would know-- anyone

00:24:11.930 --> 00:24:13.735
who should care about factoring
polynomials.

00:24:13.735 --> 00:24:16.150
So I got together a whole bunch
of educators and said,

00:24:16.150 --> 00:24:18.230
let's make a video on motivating
to students why

00:24:18.230 --> 00:24:20.180
they should care about factoring
polynomials.

00:24:20.180 --> 00:24:21.110
And there's no answer.

00:24:21.110 --> 00:24:22.810
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:22.810 --> 00:24:24.810
SEBASTIAN THRUN: It's like, some
mathematicians wrote it

00:24:24.810 --> 00:24:27.330
into the books a long time ago
and said this is part of it.

00:24:27.330 --> 00:24:29.220
And you'll be foregoing all
these other opportunities.

00:24:29.220 --> 00:24:32.680
I think if I had a choice and
go to a 16-year-old and

00:24:32.680 --> 00:24:34.530
[? say ?] learn about factoring
polynomials or learn

00:24:34.530 --> 00:24:36.950
HTML5, you should learn HTML5.

00:24:36.950 --> 00:24:38.944
Because that's so much cooler.

00:24:38.944 --> 00:24:41.030
PETER LUBBERS: In fact,
I can attest to that.

00:24:41.030 --> 00:24:43.556
I have a 15 and a
17-year-old son.

00:24:43.556 --> 00:24:44.472
They'd agree.

00:24:44.472 --> 00:24:44.930
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:44.930 --> 00:24:46.830
SEBASTIAN THRUN: I think there's
a lot to be done.

00:24:46.830 --> 00:24:49.610
I think everybody should be
able to be a teacher.

00:24:49.610 --> 00:24:51.340
Everybody should be able
to be a student and a

00:24:51.340 --> 00:24:52.480
teacher at the same time.

00:24:52.480 --> 00:24:54.940
Being a teacher is the best
way to be a student.

00:24:54.940 --> 00:24:56.970
We should discover what makes
teaching go well.

00:24:56.970 --> 00:24:59.420
I just refuse to believe that a
lecture class with like 500

00:24:59.420 --> 00:25:02.290
and kids and a professor
lecturing chemistry is the

00:25:02.290 --> 00:25:03.960
best that society can do.

00:25:03.960 --> 00:25:05.840
It's probably the best you
could do 300 years ago.

00:25:05.840 --> 00:25:07.660
But guys, wake up.

00:25:07.660 --> 00:25:09.235
We live in the 21st century.

00:25:09.235 --> 00:25:10.560
KATHERINE MILLER: Fair enough.

00:25:10.560 --> 00:25:12.610
Fair enough.

00:25:12.610 --> 00:25:19.070
So with that, an interesting
thing that we are doing with

00:25:19.070 --> 00:25:20.550
this is a little bit
of a hybrid model.

00:25:20.550 --> 00:25:23.040
There actually is an
in-person component

00:25:23.040 --> 00:25:23.750
to this, isn't there?

00:25:23.750 --> 00:25:24.890
SEAN BENNETT: That's right.

00:25:24.890 --> 00:25:25.053
Yeah.

00:25:25.053 --> 00:25:26.700
So we're trying something
new out.

00:25:26.700 --> 00:25:28.480
And really excited about it.

00:25:28.480 --> 00:25:31.750
It's basically a study group.

00:25:31.750 --> 00:25:35.270
So we are launching,
basically, a

00:25:35.270 --> 00:25:38.470
unit or two per week.

00:25:38.470 --> 00:25:41.510
And what we figured is there's a
lot of people-- for example,

00:25:41.510 --> 00:25:44.350
I run the San Francisco
HTML5 user group--

00:25:44.350 --> 00:25:48.300
there's a bunch of Udacity
Meetups in the Bay Area.

00:25:48.300 --> 00:25:54.100
And we said, why don't we get
together a nice room-- like

00:25:54.100 --> 00:25:56.150
100 people can fit
in this room--

00:25:56.150 --> 00:25:59.450
and do like office hours
or study group?

00:25:59.450 --> 00:26:02.560
And so what was interesting
about that is, we will also be

00:26:02.560 --> 00:26:03.760
live streaming that.

00:26:03.760 --> 00:26:07.690
So starting next week, on
Wednesday-- and we'll put the

00:26:07.690 --> 00:26:08.940
link to that--

00:26:08.940 --> 00:26:12.530
we're going to have, basically,
a series of-- well,

00:26:12.530 --> 00:26:13.310
it starts on Wednesday.

00:26:13.310 --> 00:26:15.130
But it's going to be
every Monday night.

00:26:15.130 --> 00:26:16.374
And we're going to be--

00:26:16.374 --> 00:26:16.771
[LAUGHTER]

00:26:16.771 --> 00:26:18.882
SEAN BENNETT: Well,
Presidents' Day.

00:26:18.882 --> 00:26:19.800
PETER LUBBERS: Exactly.

00:26:19.800 --> 00:26:20.010
Yeah.

00:26:20.010 --> 00:26:21.560
Because of the holiday.

00:26:21.560 --> 00:26:24.040
So we're going to be doing this
for about eight weeks on

00:26:24.040 --> 00:26:25.250
Monday nights.

00:26:25.250 --> 00:26:27.745
And so we'll be there--

00:26:27.745 --> 00:26:30.350
Colt, Sean, myself
will be there.

00:26:30.350 --> 00:26:32.130
Maybe Sebastian will be there.

00:26:32.130 --> 00:26:33.220
SEBASTIAN THRUN: I hope so.

00:26:33.220 --> 00:26:35.220
PETER LUBBERS: And we'll
actually deal

00:26:35.220 --> 00:26:35.750
with people's problems.

00:26:35.750 --> 00:26:39.600
So the idea is people would
take the course.

00:26:39.600 --> 00:26:44.050
They will do everything
in a unit.

00:26:44.050 --> 00:26:47.605
And then bring all their
questions to the live stream,

00:26:47.605 --> 00:26:48.580
to the room.

00:26:48.580 --> 00:26:50.720
And we'll deal with
all the questions.

00:26:50.720 --> 00:26:53.240
And we'll have a Moderator
up like we had for today.

00:26:53.240 --> 00:26:56.010
So really trying to couple
that a little bit.

00:26:56.010 --> 00:26:57.760
At least for the first
eight weeks.

00:26:57.760 --> 00:26:59.560
We're not going to keep doing
that indefinitely.

00:26:59.560 --> 00:27:02.740
And of course, after that, it's
completely self-serve,

00:27:02.740 --> 00:27:04.310
the same as everything else.

00:27:04.310 --> 00:27:07.316
But it'll be an interesting
experiment.

00:27:07.316 --> 00:27:11.230
KATHERINE MILLER: And have any
of your other courses had this

00:27:11.230 --> 00:27:13.180
hybrid component to them?

00:27:13.180 --> 00:27:15.440
SEAN BENNETT: The closest we've
come, I think, is Office

00:27:15.440 --> 00:27:18.040
Hours when we originally
started, where we would just

00:27:18.040 --> 00:27:19.790
have videos that we
would put up.

00:27:19.790 --> 00:27:21.320
Students would ask questions
in the forum.

00:27:21.320 --> 00:27:23.080
And then the most popular
questions, we would answer in

00:27:23.080 --> 00:27:25.850
a short segment and put
them up on a more

00:27:25.850 --> 00:27:26.860
or less weekly basis.

00:27:26.860 --> 00:27:27.450
SEBASTIAN THRUN: Yeah.

00:27:27.450 --> 00:27:28.860
So Peter and I had
a Google Hangout.

00:27:28.860 --> 00:27:31.130
It was also broadcast
over YouTube.

00:27:31.130 --> 00:27:34.080
And we had 12,000 students at
the same time online just

00:27:34.080 --> 00:27:35.500
listening to their
conversation.

00:27:35.500 --> 00:27:36.910
And we picked student
questions.

00:27:36.910 --> 00:27:38.350
And we didn't pick all
12,000 obviously.

00:27:38.350 --> 00:27:39.826
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:39.826 --> 00:27:41.570
SEBASTIAN THRUN: We used a
Google Moderator to have

00:27:41.570 --> 00:27:42.240
people brought [? up ?]

00:27:42.240 --> 00:27:42.790
[? all these ?]

00:27:42.790 --> 00:27:43.280
questions.

00:27:43.280 --> 00:27:45.640
And even 12,000 students don't
have 12,000 questions.

00:27:45.640 --> 00:27:47.690
They have maybe 20,
30, 50 questions.

00:27:47.690 --> 00:27:50.050
PETER LUBBERS: Well, that's
precisely the huge

00:27:50.050 --> 00:27:50.895
benefit of the scale.

00:27:50.895 --> 00:27:52.330
SEBASTIAN THRUN: And the
interesting thing was, half

00:27:52.330 --> 00:27:53.430
the questions were
technical and the

00:27:53.430 --> 00:27:54.280
other half were personal.

00:27:54.280 --> 00:27:56.250
Like, what does it mean
to work at Google?

00:27:56.250 --> 00:27:57.690
What does it mean to work
in the United States?

00:27:57.690 --> 00:28:00.180
As a German-- or
as a European--

00:28:00.180 --> 00:28:00.780
how to get there.

00:28:00.780 --> 00:28:02.170
And it was really interesting
to see how much people

00:28:02.170 --> 00:28:03.240
benefited from that
discussion.

00:28:03.240 --> 00:28:04.040
KATHERINE MILLER: I see.

00:28:04.040 --> 00:28:07.660
It really does seem like
they're just really

00:28:07.660 --> 00:28:12.420
interesting, innovative ways
to be making it scalable,

00:28:12.420 --> 00:28:12.835
accessible.

00:28:12.835 --> 00:28:16.910
And yet at the same time really
addressing the benefits

00:28:16.910 --> 00:28:18.880
of what it is to be
in a classroom.

00:28:18.880 --> 00:28:22.750
That while the lecture format
may no longer be as relevant,

00:28:22.750 --> 00:28:25.150
there's still the benefits
of interacting with the

00:28:25.150 --> 00:28:27.110
professor, interacting with
your fellow students.

00:28:27.110 --> 00:28:29.350
And it sounds like you've
come up with some really

00:28:29.350 --> 00:28:32.750
interesting ways of doing that
without removing the human

00:28:32.750 --> 00:28:33.800
element, if you will.

00:28:33.800 --> 00:28:34.310
PETER LUBBERS: Yeah.

00:28:34.310 --> 00:28:35.490
We didn't want to just, OK.

00:28:35.490 --> 00:28:36.120
It's finished.

00:28:36.120 --> 00:28:36.850
Goodbye.

00:28:36.850 --> 00:28:37.920
We'll move on to the
next project.

00:28:37.920 --> 00:28:40.620
We want to really also
learn from--

00:28:40.620 --> 00:28:42.560
clearly there's ways that
we can improve.

00:28:42.560 --> 00:28:45.750
And we can get a much closer
look if we keep the finger on

00:28:45.750 --> 00:28:47.450
the pulse of what is
actually happening.

